# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: africa-t20-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:africa-t20-cup/2015-africa-t20-cup] The **2015 Africa T20 Cup** was a Twenty20 cricket tournament held in South Africa from 4 September to 4 October 2015, as a curtain-raiser to the 2015–16 South African domestic season.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2015-africa-t20-cup] Organized by Cricket South Africa, it featured thirteen South African provincial teams, as well as a Zimbabwean development XI and the national sides of Kenya and Namibia.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2015-africa-t20-cup] The sixteen participating teams were split into four pools of four, with the teams from each pool playing all of their matches at one ground across a single weekend.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2015-africa-t20-cup] Benoni, Potchefstroom, Kimberley, and Bloemfontein hosted matches, as other venues were unavailable at that point in the season.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2015-africa-t20-cup] Northerns defeated KwaZulu-Natal Inland in the final, which was held at Bloemfontein's Mangaung Oval.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2015-africa-t20-cup] The tournament's leading runscorer was KZN Inland's Vaughn van Jaarsveld, while four players shared the leading wicket taker title.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2015-africa-t20-cup] Note: Justin Ontong was originally named in Boland's squad, but withdrew to focus on his recovery from knee surgery.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2015-africa-t20-cup] The top five runscorers are included in this table, ranked by runs scored, then by batting average, then alphabetically by surname.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2015-africa-t20-cup] The top five wicket takers are listed in this table, ranked by wickets taken and then by bowling average.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2016-africa-t20-cup] The **2016 Africa T20 Cup** was the second edition of the Africa T20 Cup, a Twenty20 cricket tournament that was held in South Africa from 2 September to 1 October 2016, as a curtain-raiser to the 2016–17 South African domestic season.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2016-africa-t20-cup] Organised by Cricket South Africa, it featured thirteen South African provincial teams, as well as the national sides of Kenya, Namibia and Zimbabwe.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2016-africa-t20-cup] Defending champions Northerns were drawn in Pool B.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2016-africa-t20-cup] In Pool C four of the six matches were abandoned due to rain.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2016-africa-t20-cup] Under the rules of the tournament, all the matches in that group were declared null and void.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2016-africa-t20-cup] An elimination draw was then conducted with the captains of each team in the group, with Zimbabwe progressing to the finals section of the cup.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2016-africa-t20-cup] The Recreation Ground in Oudtshoorn was chosen at the venue for the semi-finals and final.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2016-africa-t20-cup] Eastern Province won the tournament, beating Northern Cape by 31 runs in the final.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2016-africa-t20-cup] With four of the games being abandoned, an elimination draw was done with Zimbabwe progressing to the finals stage.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2017-africa-t20-cup] The **2017 Africa T20 Cup** was the third edition of the Africa T20 Cup, a Twenty20 cricket tournament.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2017-africa-t20-cup] It was held in South Africa from 25 August to 25 September 2017, as a curtain-raiser to the 2017–18 South African domestic season.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2017-africa-t20-cup] Organised by Cricket South Africa, it featured thirteen South African provincial teams, as well as national representative sides of Kenya, Namibia and Zimbabwe.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2017-africa-t20-cup] Defending champions Eastern Province were drawn in Pool B.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2017-africa-t20-cup] Namibia won all three games in Group A, progressing to the semi-finals of the tournament for the first time.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2017-africa-t20-cup] Gauteng also progressed to the semi-finals for the first time, after winning Group B.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2017-africa-t20-cup] They topped the table with a bonus-point win in their final group match, knocking out defending champions Eastern Province in the process.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2017-africa-t20-cup] In Group C, Free State progressed, after beating Northern Cape by 62 runs in the final match of the group.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2017-africa-t20-cup] KwaZulu-Natal Inland progressed from Group D after beating Border by six wickets in their final group fixture.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2017-africa-t20-cup] In the first semi-final, KwaZulu-Natal Inland beat Gauteng by 8 wickets to progress to the final.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2017-africa-t20-cup] They were joined in the final with Free State, who beat Namibia by 10 wickets.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2017-africa-t20-cup] Andries Gous scored a century, the second-ever in the Africa T20 Cup.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2017-africa-t20-cup] KwaZulu-Natal Inland won the tournament, beating Free State by 6 wickets in the final.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] The **2018 Africa T20 Cup** was the fourth and final edition of the Africa T20 Cup, a Twenty20 cricket tournament.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] It was held in South Africa in September 2018, as a curtain-raiser to the 2018–19 South African domestic season.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] Provincial side KwaZulu-Natal Inland were the defending champions.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] Organised by Cricket South Africa, the tournament featured 20 teams.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] Sixteen of these teams had participated in previous years – thirteen South African provincial teams, national representative sides of Kenya, Namibia and Zimbabwe – and they were joined by South African teams Limpopo and Mpumalanga along with the national teams of Nigeria and Uganda.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] The invitation was initially extended to Ghana, but they declined and Uganda was invited in their place.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] Uganda's captain, Roger Mukasa, said it would give the team "a priceless chance to get international exposure" ahead of the 2018 ICC World Cricket League Division Three tournament.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] On the opening day of the tournament, Marco Marais scored an unbeaten century for Border against Namibia in Group C.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] In Group D, Shane Dadswell scored 98 runs from 34 balls for North West, which Cricket South Africa described as "the performance of the day".
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] Marais scored his second century on the second day, making 106 not out.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] Wihan Lubbe also scored a century, batting for North West against Limpopo in Group D.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] In the same match, North West scored 262 runs, the second-highest score in T20 cricket.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] Following the conclusion of the group stage of the tournament, Easterns, Gauteng, Border and North West had all progressed to the semi-finals of the competition.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] Gauteng and North West were drawn together in the first semi-final, with Border and Easterns playing each other in the second semi-final.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] The matches took place at Buffalo Park in East London.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] In the first semi-final, Gauteng beat North West by 27 runs to progress to the final.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] They were joined by Border, after they beat Easterns by 7 wickets in the second semi-final.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] Gauteng won the tournament, beating Border by three wickets in the final.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2018-africa-t20-cup] For the next season, the tournament was replaced with the returning CSA Provincial T20 Cup, last played in the 2015–16 season, and featuring only the South African domestic provincial teams.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] The **2019–20 CSA Provincial T20 Cup** was a domestic Twenty cricket tournament that took place in South Africa in September 2019, as a curtain-raiser to the 2019–20 South African domestic season.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] It was played between the thirteen South African provincial teams, along with Limpopo and Mpumalanga.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] This was the sixth edition of the CSA Provincial T20 Cup, which was last played in the 2015–16 season.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] With only domestic teams from South Africa taking part, the tournament returned in place of the Africa T20 Cup, which had been held since 2015.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] On the opening day of matches, Jonathan Vandiar scored an unbeaten century for Northerns against Gauteng in Pool A.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] In Pool B, Lauren Agenbag became the first woman to umpire in a senior men's provincial match, when she was one of the on-field umpires in the match between Eastern Province and KwaZulu-Natal Inland.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] In Pool C, the match between Western Province cricket team and North West finished in a tie, with North West winning the Super Over.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] Day two of the tournament saw the second tied match in as many days, as KwaZulu-Natal and Easterns finished level on runs in Pool A, with Easterns winning the Super Over.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] In Pool B, Jacques Snyman scored 117 runs from 58 balls, as Northern Cape beat South Western Districts by 82 runs.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] Finally in Pool C, Lerato Kgoatle scored his second century in four innings, as Limpopo beat Western Province by 10 wickets.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] The third and final day of round-robin matches saw KwaZulu-Natal tie their second match in as many days in Pool A, eventually winning the Super Over against Free State.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] Easterns, Eastern Province and Border all won their respective groups to progress to the finals of the tournament.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] They were joined by KwaZulu-Natal Inland, the next best team overall, who finished second in Pool B, and above Limpopo in Pool C on net run rate.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] On 16 September 2019, Cricket South Africa confirmed the draw for the semi-final matches.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] Eastern Province played KwaZulu-Natal Inland in the first semi-final, and Easterns faced Border in the second match.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] All the knock-out fixtures, including the final, took place at Willowmoore Park in Benoni.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] KwaZulu-Natal Inland won their semi-final by 21 runs, with Easterns winning their match by nine wickets, with both teams advancing to the final.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] Easterns won the tournament, beating KwaZulu-Natal Inland by five runs in the final.
[src:africa-t20-cup/2019-20-csa-provincial-t20-cup] Grant Thomson, the captain of the Easterns team, said that "it was an excellent game, an excellent final and great end to the competition".
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] The **Afghanistan Premier League** (Pashto: د افغانستان غوره لیګ; Urdu: لیگ برتر افغانيرت), officially **Gulbahar Afghanistan Premier League** for sponsorship reasons, was a Twenty20 cricket franchise tournament run by the Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB).
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] Founded in 2018, five teams were selected to compete, named after regions of Afghanistan.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] The only tournament took place between 5 and 21 October 2018 at the Sharjah Cricket Stadium, with up to forty overseas players involved.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] In August 2018, the International Cricket Council (ICC) approved plans for the tournament.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] In September 2018, the Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) announced that they would not give No Objection Certificates (NOCs) to the active Pakistani players.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] In October 2018, the Bangladesh Cricket Board (BCB) denied to give NOCs to Mohammad Mithun and Soumya Sarkar.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] Balkh Legends won the maiden title, after beating Kabul Zwanan by four wickets in the final.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] The creation of the Afghanistan Premier League followed Afghanistan's rapid rise in international cricket and its attainment of Full Member status in the International Cricket Council (ICC) in 2017.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] Following the success of Afghan players in global tournaments like the Indian Premier League (IPL) and the Big Bash League, the Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) sought to establish a high-profile domestic T20 league.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] The primary objectives were to provide local players with exposure to international standards, improve the board's financial independence, and bring high-level cricket to Afghan fans, although matches were ultimately held in the United Arab Emirates due to security considerations.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] The Afghanistan Premier League (APL) was established by the Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) in 2018 to provide a professional platform for domestic talent following the country's attainment of Full Member status.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] The inaugural season of the APL was launched in October 2018 at the Sharjah Cricket Stadium.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] The tournament featured five franchises representing different regions of Afghanistan: Balkh Legends, Kabul Zwanan, Kandahar Knights, Nangarhar Leopards, and Paktia Panthers.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] The league attracted significant international attention, with veteran stars such as Chris Gayle, Shahid Afridi, Brendon McCullum, and Andre Russell participating.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] The tournament concluded with the Balkh Legends, captained by Mohammad Nabi, defeating Kabul Zwanan to become the first-ever champions.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] Despite the sporting success of the first season, the league faced immediate administrative challenges.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] In September 2019, the ACB officially terminated its agreement with the commercial partner, Snooker City, citing non-payment of rights fees and lack of transparency.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] The league was subsequently suspended due to governance concerns and delayed player payments.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] Over the following years, the combination of the COVID-19 pandemic and political transitions within Afghanistan further delayed any attempts at a restart.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] Following the inaugural 2018 season, the league faced a major legal crisis.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] In September 2019, the ACB terminated its 10-year commercial agreement with Snixer Sports, citing material breaches and integrity risks.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] This led to a US$15 million lawsuit filed by Snixer Sports in a London arbitration court, which brought international attention to the league's governance.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] In June 2024, the ACB confirmed that they were in the final stages of planning a relaunch for the tournament.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] The board cited the need for a premier T20 platform to sustain the development of the national team.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] In December 2024, it was announced that the tournament is officially scheduled to return in October 2026, with the UAE likely to host the matches once again.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] In December 2025, the ACB officially announced the return of the league.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] The second edition is scheduled for October 2026, with the board citing the league as essential for the continued development of the Afghanistan national cricket team.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] A summary of the most notable statistical records associated with the tournament is provided below.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] The Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) awarded the global media rights for the inaugural season to a consortium led by ITW and Trans Group.
[src:africa-t20-cup/afghanistan-premier-league] For the 2018 season, the league was broadcast in over 10 countries through various television and digital platforms.
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] The **Africa T20 Cup** was a Twenty20 cricket tournament organised by Cricket South Africa.
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] It featured a combination of South African provincial teams and teams representing other African countries, including Kenya, Namibia, and Zimbabwe.
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] It ran for four years before being replaced by the CSA Provincial T20 Cup.
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] The first edition of the tournament was played in September and October 2015, as a precursor to the 2015–16 South African domestic season.
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] It was won by Northerns, which defeated KwaZulu-Natal Inland in the final by seven wickets.
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] The second edition of the tournament was played in September and October 2016.
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] It was won by Eastern Province, who defeated Northern Cape in the final by 31 runs.
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] The Africa T20 Cup has been characterised as "essentially a showcase in cricket development".
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] The South African teams have various restrictions on the composition of their squads – they had to feature no more than four players from the professional franchises, at least two players under the age of 21, and at least six players of colour (including at least three Black Africans).
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] The Africa T20 Cup partially filled the gap left in the South African calendar by the cancellation of the Champions League Twenty20.
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] The SuperSport television network, a major sponsor of Cricket South Africa, was the tournament's broadcaster.
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] In 2016, it was suggested that the Africa T20 Cup would be expanded in the future to include other African countries, such as Uganda.
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] For the 2018 edition, the number of teams was increased from 16 to 20, with the addition of the South African teams of Limpopo and Mpumalanga, along with national representation from Ghana and Nigeria.
[src:africa-t20-cup/africa-t20-cup] However, Ghana declined Cricket South Africa's invite to compete in the tournament, and were replaced by Uganda.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] The **Andhra Premier League** (**APL**) is a Twenty20 franchise cricket tournament played in the state of Andhra Pradesh in India.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] It is organized by the Andhra Cricket Association (ACA) and sanctioned by the Board of Control for Cricket in India.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] It was first contested in 2022 by six teams and, as of 2026, is contested by seven.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] It is currently sponsored by GMR Group and consequently officially named the GMR APL.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] The Andhra Premier League was launched in July 2022.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] The tournament is played in a round-robin format followed by playoffs resulting in a total of 19 matches between 6 teams.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] The inaugural season of the tournament was held from 6 to 17 July 2022.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] The second season of the tournament was held from 16 to 27 August 2023.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] The third season of the tournament was held from 30 June to 13 July 2024.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] The fourth season of the tournament started from 8th August, 2025 with an opening match between the Kakinada Kings and the Amaravthi Royals.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] Andhra Pradesh High Court stays Andhra Premier League 2025 franchise auctions until further orders.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] Major relief for existing team owners challenging Andhra Cricket Association's unilateral and misleading auction process.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] Seven new franchises are competing in the league from 2025 edition.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] The franchises are named after a city it is representing in the state.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] Ahead of the 2025 season, Six franchises competing in the league were defuncted.
[src:africa-t20-cup/andhra-premier-league] The franchises were named after a city or region in the state.
